<font color="#FF0000">WELCOME HOME, MY BROTHER!</font><br>
<tt>Thu Aug 21 19:58:04 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Tankerbird, we all suffer from the benign neglect of our government.  Almost all that we (Vietnam vets) have gotten is because we fought for it.  <br>
Overcoming this &quot;I'm more of a vet than you are&quot; crap is difficult.  Attaching value to our service for this country is something that we had to fight for as well.  PTSD is real and being in-country is not a prerequisite.  How about the guy who went to Germany and the rest of his high school class went to Nam and he is the only one left?  How about the guy who was wearing a (any) uniform and was physically and verbally abused by anti-war protestors?  It didn't matter where we were in the 60's and 70's; if you were in uniform you were a bad person.  My PTSD did not come from my service in Vietnam , but is rooted in what my country did to me after I returned. <br>
I have been to the website that you refer to. It is disheartening to see either educators who promote this and students who believe it enough to post it where the world can read it.  I guess that is why we are here.  We will never educate them to see our views, and frankly, I could care less what they say.<br>
So, Wild Bill a.k.a. Tankerbird.  Welcome Home,my brother in arms.  <br>
From an old Cannon-cocking, Spam loving, North Virginian Southerner.<br>
Chet Botkins<br>
RVN 65-67<br>
1st. Cav 3/18th Arty
